50|$|The cross grain runs {{perpendicular}} to the selvedge and parallel to the weft threads. The cross grain generally has more stretch than the <b>straight</b> <b>grain</b> since the weft threads are generally looser than the warp during weaving. Most garments (like pants or shirts) are cut on the <b>straight</b> <b>grain</b> with the cross grain parallel with the floor when the wearer is standing. This allows more stretch through {{the width of the}} garment, such as in a pants leg which needs more circumferential than vertical stretch. Garments are sometimes cut on the cross grain, generally because the pieces are too wide to fit on the <b>straight</b> <b>grain.</b>|$|E
